Use of equol for treating skin diseases AbstractEquol (7-hydroxy-3(4'hydroxyphenyl)-chroman), the major metabolite of the phytoestrogen daidzein, specifically binds and blocks the hormonal action of 5α- dihydrotestosterone (DHT)in vitroandin vivo. Equol can bind circulating free DHT and sequester it from the androgen receptor, thus altering growth and physiological hormone responses that are regulated by androgens. These data suggest a novel model to explain equol's biological properties. The significance of equol's ability to specifically bind and sequester DHT from the androgen receptor have important ramifications in health and disease and may indicate a broad and important usage for equol in the treatment and prevention of androgen-mediated pathologies of skin and hair. Thus, equol can specifically bind DHT and prevent DHT's biological actions in physiological and pathophysiological processes affecting skin and hair. Claims






 1. A method of mediating androgen hormone action so as to 


ameliorate at least one condition of the skin or hair of a subject, comprising 


 administering equol, at least 1% of which is R-equol, 


 wherein R-equol binds free 5α-dihydrotestosterone and inhibits its binding with androgen receptor. 






 2. The method of claim 1 , wherein the equol comprises at least 5% of R-equol. 






 3. The method of claim 1 , wherein the equol comprises at least 10% of R-equol. 






 4. The method of claim 1 , wherein the equol comprises at least 20% of R-equol. 






 5. The method of claim 1 , wherein the equol-comprises at least 25% of R-equol. 






 6. The method of claim 1 , wherein the equol is a racemic mixture of S- equol and R-equol. 






 7. The method of claim 1 , wherein the equol further comprises S-equol in an amount sufficient to bind estrogen receptor subtypes. 






 8. A method of ameliorating at least one condition of the skin or hair of a subject, comprising: 


 administering a composition comprising equol, at least 1% of which is R-equol, wherein R-equol binds free 5α-dihydrotestosterone and inhibits its binding with androgen receptors. 






